---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const description =
  "Plain Theory Labs builds the policy certification framework for sustainable AI compute infrastructure — auditable engines that measure what clusters actually run against what they allocate, producing evidence institutions can use for policy decisions and public reporting.";

const observations = [
  ["jobs_analyzed", "73,367"],
  ["average_efficiency_score", "25.74%"],
  ["risk_flag_jobs", "65,614"],
  ["pct_short_jobs_lt_1m", "40.95%"],
  ["pct_util_zero", "33.27%"],
  ["median_util_avg", "16.00%"]
] as const;

const excerpt = `engine: ACE v0.1
mode: msa
jobs_analyzed: 73,367
average_efficiency_score: 25.74%
risk_flag_jobs: 65,614
review_queue_a: near_zero_util
review_queue_b: over_requested
review_queue_c: runtime_variance
capacity_savings_usd: computed per run
impact_model: electricity, carbon, water`;
---

<BaseLayout title="Plain Theory Labs" description={description}>
  <section class="section prose">
    <h1>Plain Theory Labs</h1>
    <p class="thesis">Policy certification infrastructure for sustainable AI compute.</p>

    <p>
      AI compute infrastructure is scaling faster than any institution's ability to measure its
      impact. Power draw, water consumption, and grid stress are documented community impacts and
      active regulatory questions. Organizations operating large GPU clusters face increasing scrutiny
      with no independent standard to point to.
    </p>

    <p>
      We are building that standard. Plain Theory Labs develops the certification framework and the
      engines that generate the evidence institutions need: auditable workload efficiency scores,
      traceable impact estimates, and structured outputs designed to hold up under regulatory review
      and public reporting requirements.
    </p>

    <p>
      ACE is the first engine. It measures what schedulers actually run against what resources they
      allocate — deterministically, from exported records, with every assumption documented.
    </p>

    <p class="inline-links">
      <a href="/ace">ACE Engine &rarr;</a>
      <span class="muted">Allocation and Cost Engine — workload efficiency scoring for GPU clusters.</span>
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>The measurement gap is a policy problem</h2>

    <p>
      Most large compute facilities already generate telemetry. Scheduler logs, DCGM traces, power
      draw records — the raw data exists. What does not exist is a defensible methodology for
      translating that data into findings: utilization rates that account for workload distribution,
      impact estimates that document their assumptions, recommendations traceable to specific jobs
      and time windows.
    </p>

    <p>
      The gap is not data collection. The gap is auditability. When a regulator asks what a
      cluster's actual GPU utilization rate is — not the dashboard average, but a measured,
      documented figure — most operators have no answer that would survive independent review.
    </p>

    <p>
      Communities near major data center campuses have been documenting water drawdown agreements,
      grid stress events, and cooling discharge impacts for years. Legislative and regulatory
      responses are accumulating. The accountability mechanisms are arriving before the measurement
      infrastructure to support them.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>A policy framework, built engine by engine</h2>

    <p>
      PTL builds modular infrastructure engines. Each engine addresses one layer of the measurement
      problem and produces structured outputs — JSON, HTML reports, versioned schemas — designed
      for institutional use and compatible with the others.
    </p>

    <p>
      ACE handles the workload layer: allocation efficiency, utilization scoring, resource
      over-request detection, and review queue generation. Subsequent engines will address carbon
      accounting (grid-source emissions per workload), water consumption modeling, and
      cross-institutional comparative benchmarking. The framework is the combination — a
      certification methodology that covers the operational footprint of a GPU cluster and produces
      evidence suitable for policy decisions and public reporting.
    </p>

    <p>
      No single metric captures the full picture. The framework is designed to be run
      incrementally: start with allocation efficiency where data is available, add carbon and water
      as telemetry improves. Every engine produces auditable outputs from the start.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>The regulatory window is open</h2>

    <p>
      The EU AI Act — in force since August 2024 — establishes energy efficiency documentation
      requirements for large-scale AI deployments. The first compliance reporting cycles will
      determine what counts as adequate methodology. State legislatures in Virginia, Texas, and
      Nevada have introduced and in some cases enacted data center disclosure requirements tied to
      water consumption, grid impact, and demonstrated efficiency. Federal AI infrastructure
      buildout plans are accelerating the scale of the problem while grid interconnection backlogs
      grow.
    </p>

    <p>
      The pattern is consistent across jurisdictions: accountability requirements arrive before
      measurement standards. The organizations that establish auditable methodology before
      compliance mandates finalize will define what the standard is — not scramble to meet someone
      else's definition of it.
    </p>

    <p>
      The window between current regulatory uncertainty and fixed compliance requirements is narrow
      and closing. That is the context in which we are building.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>The problem is auditability</h2>

    <p>
      Utilization charts are everywhere. Actionable decisions are not. The gap between raw
      telemetry and a defensible recommendation is wider than it looks — especially when the
      recommendation needs to hold up across operators, procurement, sustainability reporting, and
      institutional review.
    </p>

    <p>
      Common failure modes: recommendations that cannot be traced back to specific jobs or
      measurement windows, impact estimates built on undisclosed assumptions, and no mechanism to
      compare results across runs or configurations. You cannot improve what you cannot explain.
    </p>

    <p>
      Our engines make assumptions explicit, link every recommendation to source records, and
      produce structured outputs designed for review — not just consumption.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>What the data actually shows</h2>
    <p class="muted">
      Single institutional trace. MIT Supercloud HPCA22 dataset, converted to ACE canonical schema.
      Numbers are real. Interpretation depends on telemetry quality, workload mix, and how
      utilization is measured.
    </p>

    <div class="panel">
      <pre class="report-excerpt"><code>{excerpt}</code></pre>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Metric</th>
            <th>Value</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {observations.map(([metric, value]) => (
            <tr>
              <td><code>{metric}</code></td>
              <td>{value}</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>
      40.95% of jobs ran under one minute. Short jobs dominate scheduling overhead and disappear
      in broad utilization averages — the average looks better than the workload actually is.
    </p>

    <p>
      33.27% of jobs show near-zero GPU utilization. Together with a median utilization average of
      16%, this points to a mix of over-requesting, idle allocation, missing telemetry, and workload
      mismatch. Each category has different operational causes and different appropriate responses.
    </p>

    <p>
      65,614 jobs were flagged for review across three queues: near-zero utilization,
      over-requested resources, and runtime variance. Review queues are not enforcement — they are
      structured inputs for human decisions.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>How we work</h2>

    <p>
      We start from exported records — <code>sacct</code> output, scheduler logs, DCGM telemetry,
      CSV traces — and convert them into a canonical schema with explicit provenance. From there,
      ACE scores each job, applies safety controls that block unsafe downsizing recommendations,
      models impact across electricity, carbon, and water, and writes structured JSON and
      human-readable HTML that you can version, diff, and share.
    </p>

    <p>
      No agent access to production schedulers. No enforcement. No changes to running systems.
      Every output is traceable to source records and every assumption is documented so you can
      replace them with your own.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>Open by default</h2>

    <p>
      Scientific progress is collective. We publish methods, schemas, and write-ups when it is
      safe to share, with a focus on reproducibility and clear assumptions so others can inspect,
      challenge, and improve the work. Validation against public datasets is a first principle,
      not an afterthought.
    </p>

    <p class="inline-links"><a href="/contact">Work with us &rarr;</a></p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
